92
00:06:24,303 --> 00:06:30,066
we need to ask if it is a simulation, a representation, or an abstraction.

93
00:06:30,066 --> 00:06:35,609
For a simulation, the emotion in the game matches the one that we seek to trigger directly in the

94
00:06:35,609 --> 00:06:38,831
player. Here we want the player to feel exactly what's in the game.

95
00:06:39,707 --> 00:06:44,670
For a representation, the emotion in the game doesn't match the one that we see to trigger in

96
00:06:44,670 --> 00:06:51,674
the player. It's triggered indirectly or both. Here we put some distance between the emotion

97
00:06:51,674 --> 00:06:57,178
in the game and the player's emotion. And to bridge this gap, the player will need to interpret

98
00:06:57,178 --> 00:07:03,642
what we've given them. Abstraction. In an abstraction, we present the emotions only as

99
00:07:03,642 --> 00:07:07,364
a concept. We don't intend the player to have an emotional reaction at this point.

100
00:07:08,174 --> 00:07:10,115
Okay, let's look at each of these in turn.

101
00:07:10,115 --> 00:07:11,256
Simulation.

102
00:07:11,256 --> 00:07:13,478
In this VR simulation game,

103
00:07:13,478 --> 00:07:18,762
the player is asked to walk over a plank that's suspended over a big drop.

104
00:07:18,762 --> 00:07:21,524
Here, the emotional reaction the developer seeks to create

105
00:07:21,524 --> 00:07:25,808
calls on the player's own natural response to height.

106
00:07:25,808 --> 00:07:29,051
The game intends to generate fear directly in the player.

107
00:07:29,875 --> 00:07:36,304
In a Formula One driving simulation, the intention is to create the same emotional experience for the player as if they were driving the real car.

108
00:07:36,304 --> 00:07:38,648
Exactly what Sid Meier was asking for.

109
00:07:40,325 --> 00:07:44,387
But remember though, when we're talking about emotions, we're not necessarily simulating

110
00:07:44,387 --> 00:07:50,011
the environment or the subject. Pong is not a tennis simulator. There's no tennis court

111
00:07:50,011 --> 00:07:55,755
and the rules are different. Pong is a skill game. What's important here is that the emotions

112
00:07:55,755 --> 00:08:01,719
the game intends to create, success, win, loss, are the ones that the game intends to

113
00:08:01,719 --> 00:08:05,021
generate directly in the player. The emotions match the mechanics.

114
00:08:06,041 --> 00:08:11,470
Such emotional simulations can be so powerful that they're being used to change how people

115
00:08:11,470 --> 00:08:13,013
behave in the real world.

116
00:08:14,164 --> 00:08:18,927
Some companies are putting people into virtual situations to help them recognise racial or

117
00:08:18,927 --> 00:08:23,830
gender bias in themselves when interviewing. Doctors are being trained how to tell patients

118
00:08:23,830 --> 00:08:29,994
bad news. In each case, the participants enter the scenario as themselves and are then asked

119
00:08:29,994 --> 00:08:35,337
to respond to it directly. The emotions they're intended to feel are the ones that they would be

120
00:08:35,337 --> 00:08:37,558
feeling if they were in the real situation.

121
00:08:39,306 --> 00:08:44,291
But when it comes to representation, the experience is no longer direct.

122
00:08:44,291 --> 00:08:48,315
The game places something between the player and the emotion in the game.

123
00:08:48,315 --> 00:08:50,857
An obvious example of that would be a character.

124
00:08:52,441 --> 00:08:56,482
If we were to take the same VR training in the same doctor, but we were to ask the doctor

125
00:08:56,482 --> 00:09:00,864
to play a character this time, then the scenario would switch from being a simulation to a

126
00:09:00,864 --> 00:09:07,186
representation. Same doctor, same scenario, same emotional content. But the doctor wouldn't

127
00:09:07,186 --> 00:09:11,987
be playing and feeling as themselves. Their emotion is no longer direct. We've changed

128
00:09:11,987 --> 00:09:15,568
the way that we've asked the participants to react to it, so we've changed the experience.

129
00:09:17,392 --> 00:09:22,413
Similarly, when the plank game puts the player in a place where they're asked to feel the terror of

130
00:09:22,413 --> 00:09:30,235
crossing over that divide, when we put a character in the place, it's no longer the player who's in

131
00:09:30,235 --> 00:09:36,157
virtual danger, it's the character. Here the game doesn't ask the player to feel the same emotions

132
00:09:36,157 --> 00:09:41,599
as the character. Instead of terror, the game is asking us to feel thrill or excitement or to feel

133
00:09:41,599 --> 00:09:44,560
scared for the character rather than from ourselves.

134
00:09:45,344 --> 00:09:50,312
So we're putting a distance here between the player's own feelings and those in a game.

135
00:09:50,312 --> 00:09:51,834
Why would we want to do that?

136
00:09:51,834 --> 00:09:55,580
Well, for a start, interpretation isn't necessarily bad.

137
00:09:55,580 --> 00:10:00,988
Interpretation is itself an active verb. It's a way to make emotion interactive.

138
00:10:03,414 --> 00:10:07,037
Another plus with representation is it can allow us to present the player with a wider

139
00:10:07,037 --> 00:10:10,901
range of experiences than we can in straight simulation.

140
00:10:10,901 --> 00:10:15,505
We don't want to expose players to the true horror of war, but we can represent it.

141
00:10:15,505 --> 00:10:18,767
We can use a character as a barrier to this negative emotion.

142
00:10:18,767 --> 00:10:23,652
This can give the player an emotional distance to explore such difficult subjects.

143
00:10:23,872 --> 00:10:28,293
Using this technique, the character can be put through all sorts of potentially negative emotional

144
00:10:28,293 --> 00:10:34,034
states such as loss, rage, grief, hate, revenge, without asking the player to experience those

145
00:10:34,034 --> 00:10:40,836
emotions themselves directly. As the character feels loss, the player can feel sorry for them.

146
00:10:40,836 --> 00:10:45,398
They can connect to the character but without feeling exactly the same emotion that's in the game.

147
00:10:46,533 --> 00:10:49,875
And it's not just emotion that representation can filter.

148
00:10:49,875 --> 00:10:52,918
Just as Pong distills tennis into a simpler interactive

149
00:10:52,918 --> 00:10:54,699
and emotional experience,

150
00:10:54,699 --> 00:10:57,381
we can deconstruct other scenarios

151
00:10:57,381 --> 00:10:59,683
into their emotional components

152
00:10:59,683 --> 00:11:01,564
to find a way that suits our game

153
00:11:01,564 --> 00:11:03,866
or the emotions that we want to explore.

154
00:11:03,866 --> 00:11:06,368
When we portray love in a game,

155
00:11:06,368 --> 00:11:09,230
for instance, we're generally not presenting the player

156
00:11:09,230 --> 00:11:10,631
with the whole experience,

157
00:11:10,631 --> 00:11:12,532
just as we don't in games with war.

158
00:11:16,300 --> 00:11:19,823
In a lot of dating games, we don't deal with the choice of what to wear, the stress of

159
00:11:19,823 --> 00:11:22,205
another person taking 20 minutes to text back.

160
00:11:22,205 --> 00:11:27,109
Generally, games seek to shorten and focus the experience.

161
00:11:27,109 --> 00:11:31,852
The design wants to find the active verbs, not the moments of sitting and waiting for

162
00:11:31,852 --> 00:11:32,273
the text.

163
00:11:33,675 --> 00:11:36,658
But in doing so, we are taking the player away from that simulation.

164
00:11:36,658 --> 00:11:39,180
We're taking them out of the real experience,

165
00:11:39,180 --> 00:11:42,402
and that requires them to interpret and believe.

166
00:11:42,402 --> 00:11:45,245
In a shorter time than it takes in a real day to cover...

